notesStmt.note: Title from colophon (f. 352v) and beginning and end of each book.

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Medical encyclopedia in 9 books, with discussions of physiology, anatomy, pathology, diagnosis, fevers, specific diseases, surgery, fractures, poisons, and antidotes. Includes indexes, although some leaves are missing. Most leaves re-margined with pink paper; a few leaves have original margins and extensive marginal notes or commentary (f. 255v-261r).

author.persName: Jurjānī, Ismāʻīl ibn Ḥasan, 1042 or 1043-1136 or 1137

respStmt.persName: Quṭb al-Dīn Muḥammad, Shah of Khwarazm, 1097-1127

supportDesc.extent: 352 leaves : 395 x 317 (278 x 230) mm bound to 400 x 322 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, ii + 352 + ii; [1-352]; modern foliation in pencil, upper left recto. Catchwords added after re-margination, lower left verso.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 33 long lines; ruled in blind.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in naskh in black ink; pointed. 14 replacement folios written in a second hand.

decoDesc.decoNote: Illuminated text divider (f. 62v, 125v); illuminated circular medallion (f. 125r), miniature of a couple sitting under a tree (f. 214v); text block outlined in red; rubrics in red.

binding.p: 18th-century blind-stamped reddish-brown leather remnants laid down on the same color leather over boards; marbled paper pastedowns.

origin.p: The item is undated, probably copied in Persia in the 14th century.

history.provenance: Ownership stamp dated 1186? (1772-1773 CE) with inscription in ink (f. 1r); Persian customs stamp dated 1342 (f. 1r, 352v).
Formerly owned by the Hagop Kevorkian Fund; sold at auction at Sotheby's with other Kevorkian materials, 27 Apr. 1981, lot 108.
Appears in H.P. Kraus's catalog 186 (1991), no. 173.
Formerly owned by John D. Stanitz (Cleveland, Ohio), Ms. 20.
Acquired by Lawrence J. Schoenberg with other Stanitz manuscripts, Sept. 1997.
Deposit by Lawrence J. Schoenberg and Barbara Brizdle, 2011.
